# Car Rental — Project Rules for Cline

This file is the single source of truth for both Cline and Claude Code — see `CLAUDE.md` at the repo
root, which points back here instead of duplicating rules. If you edit rules, edit them here only.

## Project identity

- Project name: `car-rental` (kebab-case repo/module name)
- Application name: `Car Rental` (human-readable name used in prose)
- Application class: `CarRentalApplication`
- Root package / module path: `eu.cleankod.carrental`
- All packages/modules must start with `eu.cleankod.carrental`
- Gradle group: `eu.cleankod`
- Avoid unexplained abbreviations
- README and any docs site must consistently refer to the service as `Car Rental`

## Project scope

Required behaviour, restated as bullet points:

- The system should allow reservation of a car of a given type at a desired date and time for a given
  number of days.
- There are 3 types of cars: Sedan, SUV and van.
- The number of cars of each type is limited.
- Use unit tests to prove the system satisfies the requirements.

Explicit scope framing:

- Not intended to be production-ready; keep the implementation proportional to a small, focused scope
  (roughly two hours of effort).
- Favor depth on a few non-trivial areas over breadth across many features — depth in the areas of
  greatest interest matters more than covering every possible feature.
- Known limitations or trade-offs in the solution must be clearly noted. This is a firm requirement,
  not an optional courtesy — the README must contain an explicit limitations/trade-offs section.
- AI-assisted tools may be used for implementation; all design/implementation decisions should remain
  understood and explainable. Document AI usage briefly in the README.
- The system is *simulated*. This licenses simulating/in-memory persistence and skipping
  real infrastructure — it does **not** license skipping the reservation behaviour itself, the limited
  inventory constraint, overlap handling, or unit tests. Those four are the core requirements.
- Decisions and trade-offs must be defensible and explainable, not just present in code.

No endpoint paths, field names, or contracts are prescribed verbatim — there is no prescribed API shape.
Any REST surface is an optional convenience layer added on top of the core use case (see "Architecture
rules" and the REST API section below), not a strict requirement.

## Technology stack

<!-- Baseline — held across every project of this shape and safe to keep as-is. -->

- Java 25
- Spring Boot 4
- **Gradle Groovy DSL** with version catalog (`settings.gradle`, `build.gradle`, `gradle/libs.versions.toml`)
- JUnit 5
- AssertJ
- SLF4J with Logback
- Docker Compose
- Multi-stage Dockerfile

No Testcontainers, Micrometer, or Spring Boot Actuator: there is no container-backed dependency (DB/
broker) to test against, and no running service whose metrics/health would be meaningful to expose.
MkDocs (Material theme, Mermaid diagrams) is used for internal docs — see "Documentation rules".

## Technology choices — per project

- **Architecture pattern**: lightweight Hexagonal Architecture — see "Architecture rules" below for the
  full evaluation against plain layered and why (ADR 0001).
- **Persistence**: plain in-memory collections, guarded for thread safety. Nothing needs to survive a
  restart or be queried relationally; a real database would be disproportionate infrastructure for a
  simulated system this project's scope explicitly allows to simulate.
- **Schema migrations**: none. There is no schema.
- **Messaging**: none. This project involves a single synchronous reservation operation, not an
  event/queue-driven flow.
- **Secondary/mocked integrations**: none. There is no second system to mock — the in-memory store *is*
  the real (simulated) persistence for this system, not a stand-in for something else.
- **REST adapter**: implemented, minimal — one endpoint, `POST /api/v1/reservations` — see "REST API
  rules" below for the request-shape decision.
- **Concurrency strategy**: deliberate design concern, not an afterthought — see "Persistence rules"
  below and ADR 0002.

## Code style rules

- Use `var` only when the type is apparent from the right-hand side without checking another
  declaration (e.g. `new RentalPeriod(...)`, `catchThrowable(...)`). If the type comes from a method
  whose name doesn't announce its return type on its own (e.g. `repository.reserve(...)`), or from a
  stream/lookup chain, use an explicit type instead.

## Build rules

- Use Gradle, not Maven.
- Use: `settings.gradle`, `build.gradle`, `gradle/libs.versions.toml`, `./gradlew`
- Do not generate `pom.xml`.
- Do not use `./mvnw`.
- Dependencies must be declared through the Gradle version catalog where practical.
- Keep dependencies minimal and justified.
- Do not add libraries only to look impressive.

## Architecture rules

- Choose an architecture pattern that fits the project's actual shape — do not default to
  Hexagonal/Ports-and-Adapters out of habit; it's the right tool for some projects and overkill for
  others.
  - **Hexagonal / Ports and Adapters** earns its cost when there are multiple real inbound/outbound
    integrations and at least one is mocked or plausibly swappable. The port boundary is what makes the
    mock honest.
  - **Plain layered** (`controller` / `service` / `repository`) is more honest — and faster to build
    and explain — for a single-integration, CRUD-shaped project. Don't invent ports/adapters
    ceremony for one technology per side.
  - **Selected for this project: lightweight Hexagonal**, evaluated (not defaulted) against plain
    layered — full evaluation, including why the classic trigger above doesn't strictly apply here and
    why it's still worth it at near-zero incremental cost, is in
    `docs/decisions/0001-use-lightweight-hexagonal-architecture.md`. Kept deliberately *lightweight*:
    `adapter.in.rest`/`adapter.out.persistence` exist because those technologies are real; no *further*
    subtree is added for technologies this project doesn't have (messaging, secondary integrations).
- Prefer boring, explicit code over clever code, regardless of pattern.
- Keep the design easy to explain.
- Do not use CQRS, event sourcing, sagas, multi-module Gradle, or outbox pattern unless explicitly approved.
- Document such patterns as future improvements where appropriate.

### Hexagonal Architecture / Ports and Adapters (selected)

- Keep the domain pure and framework-free.
- Domain must not depend on: Spring, JDBC, REST/web APIs.
- Ports belong in the application layer, not in the domain layer.
- Because this project has a single cohesive feature (car reservation), package-by-feature collapses
  to a root-level split — a nested `reservation/` feature package would be redundant ceremony for one
  feature. Use this package layout:

```
eu.cleankod.carrental
  domain                  -- Car, CarType, Reservation, RentalPeriod, domain exceptions
  application
    port
      in                  -- ReserveCarUseCase
      out                 -- CarInventoryRepository
    (service impl)        -- ReservationService implementing the in-port, depending on the out-port
  adapter
    in
      rest                -- ReservationController, request/response DTOs, RestExceptionHandler
    out
      persistence          -- thread-safe in-memory CarInventoryRepository implementation
  config                   -- Spring @Configuration / @ConfigurationProperties bean wiring
```

- Use `adapter`, not `infrastructure`, as the package segment.
- Do not introduce abstractions before there are at least two concrete reasons, except for ports that
  protect external boundaries (the repository port is the one deliberate exception here — see
  "Architecture pattern" above for why).

## Domain exception rules

- Domain invariant violations must throw custom domain exceptions (subclasses of `RuntimeException` in
  the `domain` package).
- Do not throw `IllegalStateException`, `IllegalArgumentException`, or other generic JDK exceptions for
  domain rule violations.
- Custom domain exceptions are named after the violated invariant, e.g. `CarUnavailableException`
  (no unit of the requested type is free for the requested period), `InvalidRentalPeriodException`
  (a rental period was constructed with a non-positive duration).
- Each exception type maps to exactly one violated invariant — do not reuse one type for two
  conceptually different failure reasons. If a value object can be invalid in two distinct ways, that's
  either two exception types, or one of the two isn't actually a business-rule violation (see the next
  rule). Tests should then be able to identify the exact failure with a plain `isInstanceOf` — no need to
  parse messages to tell cases apart.
- A required field being `null` is a precondition, not a business-rule violation — use
  `Objects.requireNonNull`, not a custom domain exception, unless nullness itself is the rule being
  tested (e.g. "a car must have an owner").
- Exception constructors take the raw offending value(s), not a pre-built message string — the exception
  builds its own message from those values in its constructor. Only add accessor methods for the
  offending values if something actually needs to read them back; otherwise the constructed message is
  enough and extra accessors are unused surface area.
- Exception messages must identify the affected car type/period and describe the violated invariant.
- Domain exceptions are handled in a global exception handler in the adapter layer (`RestExceptionHandler`)
  — see "REST API rules" for the mapping.
- Domain methods must not catch domain exceptions — no try/catch inside domain classes.

## Domain model rules

- Domain objects should be immutable or mostly immutable.
- Prefer records where they improve clarity.
- Do not make domain objects mutable only for persistence convenience.
- Domain should model: `CarType` (enum: `SEDAN`, `SUV`, `VAN`), `RentalPeriod` (start date/time + number
  of days, with explicit, tested boundary semantics for what counts as overlapping), `Reservation`
  (a car type, a rental period, and enough identity to distinguish it from other reservations), and the
  inventory/allocation concept that enforces the limited-quantity constraint per `CarType`.
- Core business rule: a reservation for a given `CarType` and `RentalPeriod` may only succeed if at
  least one unit of that type is not already reserved for an overlapping period; the total units per
  type is fixed and limited. This is the rule the overlap-detection and allocation logic exists to
  enforce — get the boundary semantics (does a reservation ending on day N conflict with one starting on
  day N?) and the overlap test explicit and deliberate, not accidental.
- Concurrency requirement, stated explicitly in place of a messaging-style idempotency requirement (this
  system has no message redelivery to guard against): concurrent reservation attempts for the same car
  type and an overlapping period must not both succeed when only one matching unit remains available —
  the allocation step must be atomic. Do not claim thread-safety of the reservation flow unless it is
  actually exercised by a concurrent test.

## Application / service layer rules

- Application services orchestrate use cases; keep them small, explicit, and readable.
- Application services may depend on ports/interfaces and domain classes, not on adapter technologies
  directly.
- Name the inbound port after the use case (suffix `UseCase`) and the outbound port after the capability
  (suffix `Repository`):
  - `ReserveCarUseCase` — the one inbound use case; called by tests directly and, if the REST stage is
    implemented, by the REST controller.
  - `CarInventoryRepository` — outbound port for checking availability and recording a reservation.
- Do not add further `UseCase`/`Port` ceremony beyond these two — there is one operation in scope.

## Persistence rules

- In-memory collections only, guarded for thread safety (see "Concurrency strategy" above) — no
  database, no ORM, nothing to migrate.
- Persistence adapter belongs under `eu.cleankod.carrental.adapter.out.persistence`.
- Persistence adapter classes may use whatever concurrency-control mechanism is chosen (e.g. per-type
  locking, compare-and-swap, or synchronized allocation) — that choice is deliberately hidden behind
  `CarInventoryRepository` so the domain/application layers do not know or care how atomicity is
  achieved.

## REST API rules

- Endpoint: `POST /api/v1/reservations`.
- Input fields: `carType` (`SEDAN`/`SUV`/`VAN`), `start` (`LocalDateTime`), `days` (positive `int`) —
  deliberately mirrors `RentalPeriod`'s own `(start, days)` shape rather than a `start`/`end` date range.
  An end-timestamp would be more conventional for an HTTP client, but would require inventing a policy
  for what happens when the gap isn't a whole number of days (reject it? silently round it, shifting the
  actual return time the client asked for?) — that policy question is tangential to this project's
  actual scope, and the requirement's own wording ("for a given number of days") already matches the
  `days` shape. Considered and decided against the alternative, not defaulted.
- Response: `201 Created` with the created reservation (`id`, `carType`, `start`, `days`).
- Validate input using Bean Validation (`@NotNull`, `@Positive`).
- Global error handling (`RestExceptionHandler`, `@RestControllerAdvice`) maps: `CarUnavailableException`
  → `409 Conflict`; Bean Validation failures (`MethodArgumentNotValidException`) → `400 Bad Request` with
  per-field `details`; unparseable JSON/unrecognized enum values (`HttpMessageNotReadableException`) →
  `400 Bad Request`; anything else → `500 Internal Server Error` with a generic message, never the raw
  exception name/stack trace. No REST mapping for `InvalidRentalPeriodException`: Bean Validation's
  `@Positive` on `days` already rejects the same non-positive values before `RentalPeriod` is ever
  constructed from a request, so that domain exception is unreachable via this endpoint — the
  `RentalPeriod` constructor still enforces the invariant directly for any caller, REST or not.
- Error responses contain: `errorId` (random, for correlating with logs/support), `code` (stable,
  machine-readable), `message`, `details` (list, empty unless there's something field-specific to add).
- Fleet sizes (`car-rental.fleet.sedan-units`/`suv-units`/`van-units`) are externalized in
  `application.yml` via `FleetProperties`, not hardcoded in the wiring — see `CarRentalConfiguration` in
  the `config` package.

## Observability rules

- Use SLF4J with Logback for whatever logging is genuinely useful (e.g. logging a rejected reservation
  attempt with its reason).
- Micrometer, Spring Boot Actuator, and any other metrics/tracing stack are explicitly out of scope —
  there is no long-running service here for them to monitor meaningfully, and adding them would be
  infrastructure for its own sake in a small, focused project.

## Testing rules

- Pure-domain unit tests remain the primary proof of the business rule — unit tests are an explicit
  requirement. An integration test through the REST entry point additionally proves the wiring and is
  what enables refactoring/TDD without test churn (see below). No Testcontainers, no DB/broker
  integration tests: there is nothing external to integrate with.
- Use JUnit 5 and AssertJ.
- Group test methods with `@Nested` classes by the method/behaviour under test (e.g. a `Constructor`
  class, an `Overlaps` class), with plain-sentence method names inside each (`isTrueWhen...`), rather
  than prefixing every method name with the thing being tested.
- Tests should use given/when/then comments.
- Black-box by default: unit-test only pure, dependency-free classes — the domain (`RentalPeriod`,
  `Reservation`, `CarTypeInventory`, and the domain exceptions). Any class with an injected collaborator
  (the application service, the persistence adapter) is exercised through the real REST entry point
  (`ReservationControllerTest`: full Spring context, real `ReservationService` + real
  `InMemoryCarInventoryRepository`, no mocks) rather than in its own per-layer test — so internal
  refactoring of the service or adapter cannot break tests as long as the HTTP behaviour is unchanged.
  Put exhaustive capacity/overlap coverage on the pure domain class that owns the rule
  (`CarTypeInventoryTest`) plus `RentalPeriodTest` for interval/boundary semantics; prove the wiring
  once, end-to-end, through HTTP. Reserve Mockito for cases where constructing a real collaborator
  genuinely isn't practical (none currently); do not mock the domain itself. See
  `docs/decisions/0003-favor-black-box-tests-through-the-rest-entry-point.md`.
- Concurrency is the one deliberate white-box exception:
  `InMemoryCarInventoryRepositoryConcurrencyTest` races threads directly against
  `repository.reserve(...)` because reproducing tight, `CountDownLatch`-synchronized contention through
  real HTTP would be slow and non-deterministic. This is a justified exception, not a precedent for
  per-layer testing generally.
- REST tests use `@SpringBootTest(webEnvironment = RANDOM_PORT)` + `TestRestTemplate`
  (`org.springframework.boot:spring-boot-resttestclient`, plus `spring-boot-restclient` — Spring Boot 4
  split `RestTemplateBuilder`/`TestRestTemplate` out of the core test starter into their own modules)
  against the real application context — not `MockMvc`, and not a mocked use case. Fix fleet sizes via
  `@TestPropertySource` per test class so capacity-exhaustion scenarios don't depend on the production
  defaults in `application.yml`. Because the Spring context (and its singleton repository bean) is
  cached across test methods in the same class with no `@DirtiesContext`, and JUnit does not guarantee
  method execution order, give each test method a car-type/period combination that cannot collide with
  any other test's regardless of order (e.g. clearly separated months) rather than relying on
  `@DirtiesContext` or execution order.
- Test at least: a reservation succeeds when a unit of the requested type is available for the whole
  period; a reservation is rejected when no unit of that type remains available; overlapping periods for
  the same type are correctly detected and rejected; the boundary case where two periods touch but don't
  truly overlap is deliberately tested one way or the other, not left accidental; back-to-back
  (touching, non-overlapping) reservations of the same type both succeed even at one unit — proven
  end-to-end through the REST endpoint, not only as a domain rule; capacity is tracked independently
  per car type — reserving one type never consumes another's inventory (proven end-to-end); and — the
  concurrency requirement — when only one unit remains, concurrent reservation attempts for an
  overlapping period result in exactly one success and the rest rejected.
- Exception assertions must use `catchThrowable`: call `catchThrowable(...)` in the `// when` section,
  assign the result to a variable, and assert on it in the `// then` section. Never use
  `assertThatThrownBy(...)` or `assertThatExceptionOfType(...)`.

## Docker rules

- Provide a multi-stage Dockerfile and a Docker Compose file that runs the app only — no broker, no
  database container, since none exist in this design. These exist mainly so the optional REST adapter
  (if built) can be demoed; they are not required to prove the project's requirements, which unit
  tests already do.
- The Dockerfile does not build the jar — it packages a jar that must already exist in `build/libs`
  (run `./gradlew bootJar` on the host or in a CI build step first). This mirrors how a real CI pipeline
  is shaped (compile/test in one stage, package/publish the image in another) and keeps the image build
  itself fast and independent of the Gradle/JDK toolchain. `.dockerignore` sends only `build/libs/*.jar`
  into the build context, not the source tree.
- The Dockerfile then extracts that jar into Spring Boot's layer directories (`dependencies`,
  `spring-boot-loader`, `snapshot-dependencies`, `application` — via
  `java -Djarmode=tools -jar application.jar extract --layers`) in a dedicated stage, and assembles the
  runtime image from those layers ordered least- to most-changing. Rationale: a plain `COPY *.jar` puts
  the whole fat jar (all dependencies + app code) in one layer, so any code change invalidates and
  re-uploads the entire thing; splitting by Spring Boot's own layer boundaries means a code-only change
  only touches the small `application` layer, reusing the cached (and much larger) `dependencies` layer.
  This mirrors a pattern already used in another project of mine — a Docker-image-construction detail,
  not a stack decision, so no ADR.
- Disable the plain `jar` task (`tasks.named('jar') { enabled = false }` in `build.gradle`) so
  `build/libs/` contains exactly one jar (the boot jar) — otherwise the Dockerfile's wildcard
  `COPY *.jar` is ambiguous between the plain and boot jars and Docker refuses the build.
- Runtime container runs as a non-root user (`addgroup --system app && adduser --system --ingroup app
  app`, then `USER app`) — standard hardening with no downside here.

## Documentation rules

- Provide a README (created fresh at the start of real project work, not copied from the skeleton).
- README must explain: project summary, prerequisites, quick start, running tests, architecture
  overview (including why lightweight Hexagonal was chosen over plain layered), the concurrency
  approach and how it's tested, known limitations and trade-offs (an explicit requirement), AI
  usage disclosure, and a "future improvements" section. Keep it short — link to the MkDocs site for
  depth rather than duplicating it.
- Internal docs use MkDocs (Material theme) under `docs/`, covering architecture and testing strategy
  in more depth than the README; `docs/decisions/` (the ADRs) is part of the same site's nav. Diagrams
  use Mermaid (via `pymdownx.superfences`, native to the Material theme — no extra plugin needed).
- Every doc has exactly one authoritative home for its full rationale (an ADR, or the relevant
  `.clinerules` section for decisions with no ADR) — other files state the conclusion and link there,
  they do not re-derive the reasoning.
- README commands must be copy-paste verified before finalizing.
- Documentation must not overpromise features.
- "Future improvements" must not include things essential to this project (i.e. must not be used to
  wave away the core requirements: reservation flow, limited inventory, overlap handling, unit tests).

## Architecture Decision Records

- Location: `docs/decisions/`, sequentially numbered, e.g. `0001-use-lightweight-hexagonal-architecture.md`.
  Numbering starts at the first decision that actually earns an ADR — Java 25 and Gradle Groovy DSL were
  fixed inputs to this project, not evaluated choices, so they don't get one (see the exclusion below).
- Each ADR must include: title, status, context, decision drivers, considered options, advantages and
  disadvantages of each meaningful option, selected decision, rationale, consequences, known limitations
  or risks.
- Do not create ADRs for trivial naming choices or mechanical implementation details.
- Create ADRs together with the stage in which the relevant decision is made — do not front-load future
  ADRs during an earlier stage.
- Every stage that makes a significant decision must create or update the relevant ADR(s) as part of
  that stage's own commits, before the stage is considered complete.

## Commit rules

- One meaningful commit per coherent change.
- Do not batch unrelated changes.
- Commit message format: short one-line summary explaining what and why; optional extended body if useful.
- Preferred commit sequence, one group per stage (see "Branching workflow" for the matching branches):
  1. `docs: define project rules and implementation plan`
  2. `chore: establish architectural boundaries` (package skeleton + ADR 0001)
  3. `feat: implement car rental domain model` (`CarType`, `RentalPeriod`, `Reservation`, domain
     exceptions, overlap/boundary semantics + unit tests)
  4. `feat: implement car reservation use case` (`ReserveCarUseCase`, `ReservationService`,
     `CarInventoryRepository` port + unit tests against a fake repository)
  5. `feat: add thread-safe in-memory reservation storage` (concrete `CarInventoryRepository`, atomic
     allocation, concurrency tests + ADR on the concurrency strategy)
  6. `feat: expose reservation REST API` (only if this stage is undertaken)
  7. `test: restructure suite toward black-box coverage through the REST entry point` (delete
     redundant per-layer tests, add/strengthen REST-level scenarios, ADR 0003)
  8. `docs: finalize project documentation` (README, limitations/trade-offs, AI usage disclosure,
     "future improvements")
- Do not proceed to the next commit if current tests/build are broken.

## Branching workflow

- No direct commits to `master`/`main`.
- Each logical stage has its own feature branch.
- Branch naming pattern: `kebab-case` describing the stage:
  - `project-rules`
  - `architecture-boundaries`
  - `domain-model`
  - `reservation-use-case`
  - `in-memory-persistence`
  - `rest-api` (optional — only if undertaken)
  - `black-box-testing`
  - `documentation`
- Workflow per stage:
  1. User creates the branch and tells Claude Code.
  2. Claude Code implements the stage with individual commits, including any ADR(s) for that stage's
     decisions.
  3. User pushes, reviews, requests fixes if needed.
  4. User merges to `master`/`main`.
  5. User pulls `master`/`main` and tells Claude Code.
  6. Claude Code acknowledges and suggests the next branch name.
  7. Go to step 1.

## Memory bank

- Memory bank lives in `.cline/` and must be kept up to date.
- After completing each branch/stage, update these files before committing:
  - `progress.md` — mark the stage as completed, add any new stages discovered
  - `activeContext.md` — update current state, recent decisions, next steps
- After significant design decisions, update `techContext.md` if the tech context changed.
- Memory bank updates must be included in the branch's own commits, not as a separate branch.
- When resuming after an interruption, read `activeContext.md` first, then `progress.md`.

## Out of scope (document as future improvements)

- Persisting reservations beyond process memory (a real database)
- A REST API, if the optional stage is not undertaken (or, if it is, anything beyond a minimal
  synchronous create-reservation endpoint — auth, rate limiting, pagination, etc.)
- Cancelling/modifying an existing reservation (only creating one is required)
- Pricing/billing
- Full observability stack (metrics, tracing)
- CI/CD pipeline
- Kubernetes / Helm
- Authentication / authorization
- Event sourcing / CQRS / sagas / messaging of any kind
